            <div type="commentary">
                <p><!--commented out pending revision-->
                    <!--small cylindrical limestone altar (9cm high, 11cm diam.), with arch. mouldings around upper edge; very reminiscent of the gilt and silver one in the NY Metropolitan's Mag. Gr. hoard (see G&R catalogue). Inscr. in one of the middle bands, in regular letters with broken barred alpha now reads: PEDIAKRA- - -H- - - -. (sugg'd rest. of Pediakra[din]e-? (?some sort of ref. to Akradina? Better however, is Robert in BE 1953.283 who rejects this restoration and observes that this must be dedicated to Pediakrates, the Sikan hero recorded by Diod Sic 4.23.5 amongst those conquered by Herakles, and as enjoying heroic honours; cf. Pace, Arte e civilta, vol.3 (1946), p.527-29; thus, this is evidence of a cult of Pediakrates (also Pediokrates) at Syracuse; some parallel ceramic dedications at Gela (cf. IG 14.595-596). Located and photographed in Syracuse museum, inv no. pending.--></p>
            </div>
